<h1>@HI{{hazu}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vru{{}} <strong>@HI{{hazu}}</strong>
<li> @Vnai{{}} <strong>@HI{{hazu}}</strong>
<li> @Ai{{}} <strong>@HI{{hazu}}</strong>
<li> @Ana{{}} <strong>@HI{{hazu}}</strong>
<li> @N{{}} @HI{{no}} <strong>@HI{{hazu}}</strong>
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{hazu}}</strong> which indicates the speaker's belief that something will happen (or happened).
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{come}}ru <strong>hazu</strong>desuyo. kinou @KJ{{electricity^tale}}ga arimashitakara.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I'm sure he'll come. I received a phone call from him yesterday.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{hazu}}</strong> indicates an expectation based on some reliable knowledge and so it is more than
just a guess.
</p>

<p>
An expectation that something will not be the case can be expressed either by negating the sentence before <strong>@HI{{hazu}}</strong>
or by following  the sentence with <strong>@HI{{hazu}}</strong> @HI{{ha/ga nai}}. The latter construction carries heavier weight.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{hazu}}</strong> behaves as a noun so if "S <strong>@HI{{hazu}}</strong>" is a relative clause, @HI{{no}} follows it.
</p>

